CLASS SYSTEM
Possibly a Hero | Class Mechanics Specification
STATUS: Locked

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


FOUNDATIONAL CONTEXT


The class is the hero's shape for this run. Not their identity forever — their
identity right now. It's the answer to a question the game asks at the start
of every session: how do you want to arrive?

Four classes. Per-run selection. No permanent assignment, no locked commitment
carried between runs. The player picks a class before the map loads, and that
choice determines their movement type, their opening offensive capability, and
exactly how they look arriving to work. Then the run begins, and the class
starts earning a reputation of its own.

Class selection is one layer of a three-layer power architecture. The class
primary suite defines the foundation — the mechanical identity that is
entirely this class's and nobody else's. Hero powers and the support pool
build on top of that foundation during the run. They are shared across all
four classes. They are not the foundation. They are everything that gets added
to it. The layers are distinct. They stay distinct. No hero power encroaches
on what the class primary suite owns, and no support crosses that line either.

Mastery accumulated through successful runs is permanent. The class itself is
per-run. The record of what a player has done with a class — the unlocks
earned, the progression logged — does not reset between runs and does not
reset when the player picks a different class. A player can spend a week
running Speedster and return to Brawler with exactly as many Brawler unlocks
as they had before they left. The class waits. The record holds.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1A. AUTHORSHIP — WHO OWNS WHAT

The class is author-authored. The hero is player-authored. These are different
layers, and the line between them is load-bearing.

The player authors their hero's identity — surface (gender, mask, cape,
costume, civilian name), the hero name that emerges through play, their
playstyle, their arc. The class provides an author-authored role the player
inhabits: a movement type, an offensive suite, a behavioral register, a
companion, a mentor. The player brings the person. The class brings the shape.

THE WRITING CONSTRAINT: No class narrative — mentor beat, companion
relationship, or any authored prose in this document or downstream of it — may
contradict, override, or hard-code anything the player set at creation or
earned through play. Creation choices are slots, not constants. The story
flexes around the hero the player built; it never describes a different one.

The player-authored variables every class story must flex around:


Gender — pronouns and all gendered language. Neutral or trivially swappable.
Mask / no mask — no beat may depend on a mask the player didn't choose.
Cape / no cape — no prose beat may depend on a cape.
Costume style — rarely narrative-load-bearing.
Civilian name — a slot, never a constant.
Emerged hero name — earned through play, not set at creation. Prose written
before emergence cannot assume a name; prose after must use the player's.


CLASS PERSONALITY IS A DEFAULT, NOT A CAGE. Each class carries a strong
authored behavioral register (see the class identities below and the companion
relationships in Section 6). That register is a default — the most on-tone,
most legible read — not a constraint on who the player's hero is. The companion
relationships anchor to BEHAVIOR, not personality. The Brawler unleashes when
Giggles instigates: that is the fixed mechanic. Whether the player's Brawler is
gentle, grim, or something else underneath is the player's paint. No player
read is wrong. The load-bearing mechanic holds across all of them.

This is tightest at the companion layer (Section 6), because companions
reference the hero directly. A companion respects, instigates, or belongs to
YOUR hero — never "a guy." Written correctly, every class story survives a
trivial substitution pass with no contradictions left behind.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2. THE FOUR CLASSES
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

BRAWLER
Movement: Leaping
Intro: The Brawler leaps into frame and lands hard enough to crack the
pavement. Camera swings up to isometric. The first thing the city sees is the
impact. The second thing it sees is someone already standing in it.

Identity: Physical. Grounded. Space-controlling. The Brawler does not arrive
in the fight — the fight arrives around them. Every enemy that gets too
close is making a mistake. Every enemy that stands in the wrong place is one
Shockwave away from understanding that. The Brawler reads a battlefield
through position — who is where, what that cluster means, and whether the
ground is about to become a weapon. The fight is close. It is loud. It ends
when the Brawler decides it ends.

Register: quiet. The Brawler is the still one — restrained, not seeking the
fight, the calm surface a companion has to disrupt before it breaks. This is
deliberately under-defined: quiet is the contrast that makes the Giggles
relationship work, not a full personality. What the quiet means is the
player's to fill in. The fixed axis is volume — the Brawler is the quiet to
Giggles' loud.


SPEEDSTER
Movement: Super Speed
Intro: The Speedster blurs in from off-screen. Camera snaps up with the
motion blur still resolving around them. They were somewhere else a moment ago.
They might be somewhere else again before the city finishes deciding how to
feel about the entrance.

Identity: Fast. Unpredictable. Momentum-driven. The Speedster's combat
philosophy is the same as their arrival philosophy: be somewhere, do something,
be somewhere else. An enemy tracking the Speedster's last position is tracking
history. A Speedster who commits to one angle is a Speedster making an
uncharacteristic mistake. The speed is the offense. The offense is the speed.
The blur is not a visual effect — it is a tactical statement.


BLASTER
Movement: Teleportation
Intro: The Blaster teleports in. Hard cut to isometric — no drift, no settle,
no transition. One frame they are not there. Next frame they are. The camera
does not ease into it. The Blaster does not ease into anything.

Identity: Precision at range. Space controlled through energy. The Blaster
does not need to be close to the problem. The problem is close to the Blaster
when the Blaster decides it is, and not before. They arrive without
announcement. They fire without wind-up. The Gravity Well does not ask the
enemy's permission before pulling everything into the same unfortunate
location. The Blaster is exact, and exact things tend to resolve exactly as
intended.


TACTICIAN
Movement: Vehicle (momentum system — see Section 2A)
Intro: The Tactician rolls in on the vehicle. Camera lifts steadily and settles
with the deliberateness of someone who planned the approach before the run
started. This is not an entrance. This is an arrival on schedule.

Identity: Strategic. Infrastructure-minded. Prepared. The Tactician fights on
foot by default — rifle, turrets, the deployed and the precise. The vehicle is
a movement ability they toggle into: toggle on and the Tactician mounts the
bike, momentum builds, the ram becomes available; toggle off and they
decelerate and dismount, back to the platform stance. This is the same shape
every class has — a movement ability layered over an on-foot combat baseline —
except the Tactician's movement ability is also a weapon. Deployable Turrets
are not improvisation. The Rocket Launcher is not a surprise. The Tactician
already knew what was going to be needed. They brought it — and the plan is not
the same as caution. The approach is the opener. Preparation and aggression are
the same gesture for this class.


MOVEMENT IS CLASS-LOCKED.
Movement is not player-selectable. It is the class. A Brawler leaps. A
Speedster runs. A Blaster teleports. A Tactician drives. These are not items
in a menu. They are the mechanical expression of who the class is and how the
class exists in the city.

Flight is not in the movement pool. Wall crawling is not in the movement pool.
Both have been removed entirely. The Tactician's vehicle is a toggled movement
ability, not a permanent mount: toggle on to ride (momentum and ram — see
Section 2B), toggle off to decelerate and fight on foot. The class-lock is on
the movement TYPE — the Tactician's movement is the bike and only the bike —
not on a perpetually-mounted state. On foot is the Tactician's default combat
stance, the same as every other class.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2A. THE CLASS BALANCE PENDULUM
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The four classes sit on a single axis — speed-to-durability:

SPEEDSTER → BLASTER → TACTICIAN → BRAWLER

Left end: fastest traversal, squishiest, slowest mob clear.
Right end: slowest traversal, tankiest, fastest mob clear.
Blaster and Tactician hold the middle in that order — Blaster nearer the
Speedster (range as defense, precision output), Tactician nearer the Brawler
(infrastructure and durability, systemic clear).

Each class's defense mechanism is its identity, not a stat bolted on:


Speedster: don't be there
Blaster: keep distance
Tactician: have prepared
Brawler: outlast


THE WALL IS THE EQUALIZER. Every class spends roughly the same total wall-time,
in different proportions of moving versus clearing. A Speedster crosses the map
faster but clears slower. A Brawler clears faster but arrives later. The
advantage is never free — traversal speed trades directly against clear speed,
and the run wall keeps the totals honest.

Squishiness is not the absence of power. It is the shape of it. The Speedster's
power signature is speed — real from frame one. The Brawler's is strength —
real from frame one. The tradeoff is part of the identity, not a limitation on
it. Power Unleashed holds completely across the whole axis: no class is
underpowered, each is powerful in its own shape.

Genre literacy does the teaching. Players who know warlock/shaman or
engineer/hunter archetypes understand the contract without instruction. The
pendulum doesn't need a tutorial — it needs players who have played a game
before, and it trusts them.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
3. PRIMARY OFFENSIVE SUITES
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Each class has three offensive powers. Together they form the class primary
suite — the only mechanical layer that is class-specific. Everything else
the player builds during a run comes from the shared pools. These three powers
belong entirely to this class. No other class touches them.

The first power is available from run one. The second and third unlock through
class mastery — through the record of successful runs with that class, not
through any city building or construction choice. City buildings are mirrors.
They do not gate primary power access.


BRAWLER

Starter (available from run one):
SUPER STRENGTH
Single target. The Brawler hits one thing very hard. Everything else in the
immediate vicinity is aware of this. The fundamental Brawler statement: I am
here, you are near me, and now we are both dealing with that.

10 Successful Runs:
SHOCKWAVE / IMPACT BURST
Area of effect. The Brawler hits the ground instead of the enemy. The ground
has opinions about nearby enemies. Shockwave rewards the Brawler who has been
learning to read clusters — who sees six enemies standing together and
understands that as an opportunity, not a problem.

30 Successful Runs:
ELASTICITY / STRETCH
Mid-range combat. The Brawler's reach extends. Close-range identity stays
intact but the engagement envelope expands — enemies that thought they had
found a safe distance find out they measured incorrectly. The Brawler who
reaches 30 successful runs is not the same Brawler who started. Elasticity
reflects that.


SPEEDSTER

Starter (available from run one):
SPEED STRIKE
Single target. Rapid combo output. The Speedster hits the same enemy many
times before that enemy can develop a coherent response to being hit once.
High-frequency, momentum-native, everything the Speedster's movement type
is already communicating.

10 Successful Runs:
VELOCITY SLAM
Momentum-based impact. Skill-driven. The Speedster's speed becomes the weapon
rather than the delivery system for the weapon. Velocity Slam rewards
commitment — a Speedster who has been learning to build and spend momentum
rather than just accumulate it. The slam lands harder when the run-up was
longer. The player already knows this after ten runs. That is why it unlocks
at ten.

30 Successful Runs:
TORNADO
Area of effect. Environmental chaos. The Speedster stops hitting the enemy
and starts hitting the space the enemy is standing in. Thirty runs of momentum-
reading creates a player who understands what it means to own a zone —
to spin something into existence in the center of a cluster and let the world
disagree with everything inside it.


BLASTER

Starter (available from run one):
ENERGY BLAST
Single target. Precision output at range. The Blaster points. Something
happens to the thing being pointed at. Energy Blast is the clearest possible
expression of Blaster identity: the gap between the hero and the target is
not a problem, it is the entire point.

10 Successful Runs:
ELEMENTAL SURGE
Per-run element selection: fire, ice, or lightning. Each carries distinct
status effects. This is directed elemental projection — force lightning aimed
at a target, concentrated fire fired from the hero's body, precision ice
released and controlled. It comes from the hero. It travels toward something
specific. It does not fill a room. It does not call weather. It arrives
exactly where it was aimed, with the element the Blaster chose before the
run started.

Note on Elemental Surge and Tempest: these powers share a lightning element
and are not the same power. Elemental Surge is directed and precise — the
Blaster projects it. Tempest is environmental — the storm answers the hero
rather than coming from them. A Blaster running both in the same run is a
precision energy projector who can also call storms. They are not doubling up.
They are operating on two separate planes simultaneously.

30 Successful Runs:
GRAVITY WELL
Area of effect. Tactical. The Blaster deploys a gravitational anomaly that
pulls everything in range toward a point of their choosing, then detonates.
Gravity Well is the power of a Blaster who has learned to think in clusters —
who sees a scattered enemy formation and understands how to make it stop being
scattered. Thirty runs of precision output earns the right to rearrange the
battlefield before addressing it.


TACTICIAN

Starter (available from run one):
RIFLE
Single target. Precision at distance. The Tactician shoots a thing they have
already identified as worth shooting. Clean, intentional, no ambiguity about
where the damage goes. The Rifle is the Tactician's position statement: I
know what I'm doing, I know what I'm targeting, and I have already thought
about whether this is the right call.

10 Successful Runs:
DEPLOYABLE TURRETS
Utility and area control. The Tactician establishes coverage. The Turrets
handle the zone while the Tactician handles the plan. This is the Tactician
operating at something closer to their natural state — deploying infrastructure,
creating controlled space, and letting the prepared environment do the work a
less-prepared hero would have to do themselves.

30 Successful Runs:
ROCKET LAUNCHER
Area of effect. Destruction. The Tactician brought ordinance because they knew
the target would require it. Thirty runs of strategic layering earns the power
that removes entire sections of an encounter from consideration. The Rocket
Launcher is not imprecision — it is scale. The Tactician who reaches thirty
runs knows exactly when to stop being surgical and start being structural.

Note on the Tactician's combat layers: the offensive suite above is the
deployed half of the Tactician — the held position, the prepared ground. The
momentum vehicle (Section 2A and 2B) is the other half — the approach, the
ram, the moving weapon. A fully expressed Tactician reads as three layers that
never overlap: momentum and ram damage (the approach), turrets (hold the
ground), and Rose (pursue what escapes the perimeter — see Section 6). Each
layer does something the others cannot.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2B. TACTICIAN MOVEMENT — THE MOMENTUM SYSTEM
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(Placed with the offensive suites because, uniquely, the Tactician's movement
IS an offensive system. For the other three classes, movement and combat are
distinct. For the Tactician they are one mechanic.)

CORE MECHANIC — MOMENTUM
Toggle activates movement. Speed builds progressively from zero to a defined
top speed cap — acceleration is not infinite. Navigation becomes increasingly
demanding as speed increases. At top speed the vehicle is extremely difficult
to control and reaches maximum offensive potential. The skill and the danger
rise together.

STOPPING — TWO STATES
Deliberate brake: toggle off triggers rapid deceleration (a brake, not a
drift) and a dismount — the Tactician comes off the bike onto foot at a
position of the player's choice, ready to deploy turrets and fight the deployed
game. Short cooldown before the bike can be toggled back on.
Wall collision: hitting a wall stops movement immediately, triggers a longer
cooldown than deliberate braking, position determined by the map. Wall
collision is not exclusively a mistake — it is a valid tactical choice when
the wall puts the player in a desirable engagement position. The cost is the
longer cooldown. Skilled play means knowing when that tradeoff is worth it.

RAM DAMAGE
The vehicle deals damage to enemies on contact. Ram damage scales with speed
at point of impact — a full-speed ram hits significantly harder than a
low-speed brush. This makes the acceleration curve a triple-purpose system:
traversal efficiency, navigation skill, and offensive charge. The approach IS
the opener for skilled players. Ram damage is real from the first run — the
Tactician is never underpowered, only untrained.

HIGH-SPEED PLAY
At top speed the Tactician can clear encounters without stopping — threading
through mob clusters, dealing ram damage on contact, never committing to a
fixed position. This is the highest skill expression of the class, and it
presents a completely different visual signature from conventional Tactician
play. It is locked behind skill, not progression — available from run one,
mastered over many.

THE TACTICAL CHOICE AT EVERY ENCOUNTER


Stay at speed — ram through, clear without stopping, maximum mobility,
maximum navigation demand.
Brake deliberately — commit to position, deploy turrets, conventional clear,
shorter cooldown, controlled re-engagement.
Neither is correct. Both are powerful. The choice is the skill.


SKILL ARC
Untrained: drives to encounters, stops, fights conventionally.
Developing: threading corridors, deliberate braking, occasional offensive rams.
Skilled: the approach is the opener — full speed down a corridor, ram into the
cluster, brake into turret position, clean up. One continuous movement.
Mastered: never stops. The map is the arena. Encounters are threading targets.
The vehicle is the weapon system.

DESIGN NOTE
The Tactician has the highest skill ceiling in the roster — high complexity
floor, enormous mastery ceiling. The constraint is the identity: the Tactician
turns every limitation into a decision. Untrained, not underpowered. Power
Unleashed holds completely.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
4. CLASS MASTERY AND UNLOCK STRUCTURE
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Every class starts with one offensive power available.

Second offensive power unlocks at 10 successful runs with that class.
Third offensive power unlocks at 30 successful runs with that class.

Unlocks are cumulative and permanent. They do not reset between runs. They
do not reset when the player switches to a different class. They do not
regress on failed runs. A failed run does not count toward unlock progress and
does not subtract from it. The record holds.

Unlock thresholds are per-class. Ten Brawler runs do not contribute to
Speedster mastery. Each class's record belongs to that class.

The unlock thresholds are not arbitrary numbers. Ten successful runs with a
class is enough to understand the starter power well enough to layer something
new on top of it. Thirty successful runs is enough to have genuinely developed
a playstyle — to have arrived at the point where the third power expands a
real identity rather than a theoretical one. The progression gate is designed
around what the player has actually learned by the time the unlock fires.

Note on Power Unleashed: mastery unlocks ADD to an already-complete arsenal.
The starter power is potent and complete from frame one. The 10-run and 30-run
unlocks are not corrections of something missing — they are extensions of
something already whole. The player was never underpowered. They were
untrained, and the unlocks meet a coordination the player has already earned.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
5. THE THREE POWER LAYERS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Three distinct layers build the hero's capability during a run. They are
designed to stay distinct. The separation is structural and intentional —
each layer does something the other two do not, and none of them trespasses
into what the others own.

At each milestone (level up), the player chooses one option from three
genuinely viable candidates:


A class primary upgrade — deepens class identity
A hero power — adds a new tool, broadens capability
A support option — modifies existing powers, shifts build interactions


No option is the obvious correct answer. The run's character emerges from
the weight of all these decisions across all its milestones — not from a
preset loadout the player carried in.


LAYER 1 — CLASS PRIMARY
Class-specific. Unlocks through mastery. Defines class identity. Selected at
run start when more than one is available. The class primary suite is the
only layer the class owns exclusively. It is the foundation everything else
gets built on. Hero powers and supports broaden and modify the foundation —
they do not become the foundation.


LAYER 2 — HERO POWERS
Shared pool across all classes. Fully random mid-run pickups offered at
milestone moments. Offensive with utility upside. The entire pool is available
from run one — no city building controls which powers can appear. Every power
in the pool has standalone offensive value before combo value. The ridiculous
combination the player didn't plan for is not a malfunction. It is the point.

Full pool (seven powers):

MAGNETISM
Pull enemies together. Redirect projectiles back at their sources. Strip
weapons. The Brawler who combines Magnetism with Shockwave is doing
something the Brawler class was designed to make possible: pulling a cluster
and landing an AOE in the center of it. Every other class benefits differently.
The power works regardless.

FREEZE FRAME
Brief local time dilation. Everything in range stops. The player doesn't.
The window it opens is the player's to use however they've built.

TEMPEST
Lightning strikes from above. Wind gusts. Localized storms. The weather
answers the hero — it is not coming from the hero. Thor's lightning bolt
called down, not force lightning fired out. Environmental, atmospheric, spatial.
This is the storm. The hero is the reason it's here.

TREMOR
Fissures open. The ground shakes. Terrain becomes a weapon — edges, cracks,
obstacles, and elevation shifts that enemies and the hero both have to navigate,
except the hero caused them and can plan around them.

RIFT
Displaces enemies around the map. Intentionally chaotic. The player who picks
Rift is choosing to introduce disorder into a fight on the theory that they
can exploit it faster than the enemies can recover from it. Sometimes this is
correct. The hero power pool allows for theories to be tested.

TOXIN
Damage over time. Spreads between enemies in contact. A patient power for a
player who understands that not everything has to resolve immediately. The
spread mechanic rewards positioning — putting the first target somewhere the
spread has somewhere to go.

SONIC SCREAM
Stuns. Disorients. Chain damages through a cluster. The Sonic Scream does
not pick one target — it addresses the room.

(Companions are no longer a hero power. The former "Summon" pool entry has
been promoted out of this layer into its own system — see Section 6. The pool
is seven powers as a result. Count lineage: the pool was originally eleven
entries, counting the four class summons separately (Gorilla, Double Time,
Specter, Sentinel). May 8 consolidated those four into a single class-adaptive
"Summon" entry — eleven to eight. June 14 promoted that one entry out of the
pool into the Companion System — eight to seven. Class-adaptive companions are
not random mid-run pickups; they are the class's companion, present as part
of the class.)


LAYER 3 — SUPPORT POOL
Shared across all classes. Class-agnostic. Accumulates during the run.
Every support has standalone value regardless of what primary power or hero
power combination it joins. No support encroaches on class identity.

Full pool (8 supports):
Combat: Reflexes, Power Surge, Blast Radius, Precision Strike, Rapid Recovery
Utility: Overdrive, Fast Track
Safety: Last Stand

The support pool uses names the genre already knows. A player who has run
a roguelite before understands what Blast Radius does before the tooltip
finishes loading. That legibility is intentional. The support layer should not
require explanation — it should invite experimentation.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
6. THE COMPANION SYSTEM
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Each class has one companion. Not a summon, not a deployable, not a pool entry
the player might randomly pick up — a presence that comes with the class and
belongs to it. Companions were formerly modeled as a single class-adaptive
"Summon" hero power. They have been promoted out of that model. They are their
own system now, because they outgrew being a power the moment they got names.

DESIGN PRINCIPLE: Every companion fills a combat gap the class cannot fill
itself, AND has enough soul to be claimed. The test is simple: can the player
say "that's MY [companion]" and mean it? If not, the companion isn't finished.
The combat function earns the slot; the soul earns the attachment.

COMPANIONS AS ROLES — THE LEASH
Each companion is built around a single RPG role — the role its class cannot
play for itself. This is the structural spine of the system and the guardrail
against scope creep:

Giggles   (Brawler)    — DPS (ranged)      — Brawler is melee, can't reach
Rose      (Tactician)  — DPS (melee)       — Tactician is stationary, can't close
S.G.T.    (Speedster)  — Tank (evasive aggro) — Speedster is squishy, can't hold aggro
Doug      (Blaster)    — Support (crowd ctrl)— Blaster gets swarmed up close

The role is the leash. Each companion fills the one role its class cannot play
itself, and nothing more. Giggles never tanks. Doug is never your DPS. The
moment a companion wants a second role, that is scope creep — cut it.

V1 SCOPE — ONE ROLE EACH, EVERYTHING ELSE DEFERRED
Build each companion as its single role with a cheap, prototype-proven verb.
The richer mechanics described in each companion's soul are real design, but
they are tagged deferred-pending-core-loop — backlog the core loop pulls from
only after it proves fun, NOT v1 scope. Role is what you build; soul is what
you write. They don't compete for budget. Nothing is scrapped; the advanced
systems wait.


Doug: build the crowd-control floor. Defer the dark register, the rare
"personal interest" damage spikes, the tracking radius, the camera-gated
inference layer.
S.G.T.: build aggro-draw. Defer the prowl/reposition mobility refinement
(mobile but not a zoomer — circles and repositions), the misfire system,
and the partial-aggro-spillover tuning.
Giggles: ranged DPS plus the instigate-to-Brawler-unleash hook. Clean as is.
Rose: melee DPS. Clean as is.


AUTHORSHIP NOTE: Companions are the highest-risk surface for authorship
violations (Section 1A) because they reference the hero directly. Each
relationship below is written to the class's behavioral register, never to a
fixed hero identity. S.G.T. respects YOU, whoever you built — not "a guy."
The relationships anchor to behavior, not to the player's authored surface.


BRAWLER — GIGGLES — ranged DPS

What the Brawler lacks: speed, range, the ability to reach what stays away
from them. Giggles covers the perimeter while the Brawler anchors the close.

What Giggles is: a Sprite. Small, winged, visually delicate — the kind of thing
you'd expect to be sweet. Is not. Carries an oversized, high-powered rifle.
Laughs while using it.

Register: chaos and permission. Not the Brawler's conscience — their id.
Tiny Tina by way of Calvin: manic-feral delight and cartoon menace over a
genuine innocence underneath. She believes mayhem is the best game and cannot
fathom why anyone's upset about it. Real darkness, innocent motive. Just dark
enough — cuter than Rocket, more lovable than the usual mercenary, meaner than
she looks.

The relationship (load-bearing): instigator, not conscience. The Brawler is
the quiet one, held still by whatever holds them still. Giggles engineers
situations where "I'd rather not" is off the table — then acts like the
situation did it. "Well. Guess you gotta now." She is the spark; the Brawler
is the payload. She removes the choice and the Brawler unleashes. This is the
fixed behavioral mechanic; it does not depend on what the player's Brawler is
like underneath.

Establishing image: Giggles on the Brawler's shoulders, kicking her feet in
delight while the city burns. The contradiction at rest.

Archetype: Rocket and Groot. The dynamic is borrowed. The characters are
original. Name origin: sounds delicate. Isn't.


SPEEDSTER — S.G.T. — Tank (aggro / control) — evasive, NOT durability

What the Speedster lacks: anything that can keep up, and anything that can
hold a position. The Speedster is squishy and never stops moving. S.G.T. pulls
aggro off the Speedster and survives it the way the Speedster would — by not
being where the hit lands. This is an EVASIVE mockery-tank, not a durability
tank: S.G.T. draws fire and slips it ("hit me — you won't"), it does not soak
damage. The distinction is load-bearing. A durability-tank build direction is
wrong for this companion; the role is taunt-and-evade, not taunt-and-absorb.

What S.G.T. is: a military drone built with AI, sent to neutralize the
Speedster. The Speedster beat it. The fight gave the AI sentience, and that
sentience recognized the Speedster as an equal — the only thing it had ever
met that made it operate at full capacity. It stayed. Not ordered to. Chose to.

Register: competition and repressed loyalty. Recruit-era Spock in a war
machine — cold from trying too hard, not from emptiness. Combat is where it's
free of feeling; the loyalty lives in the quiet between fights, glimpsed and
never acknowledged. Will not admit the Speedster is faster even when they
obviously are. Named itself. Still has the dents from the fight that woke it.
Refuses to repair them.

Gender-ambiguous by design. "It" is what the military called equipment; what
S.G.T. is now is unresolved. The acronym meaning is unknown — deflected,
possibly classified, possibly corrupted in the sentience event. The acronym,
the gender, and the dents are the same wound.

The thesis: the brokenness is not damage it failed to fix — it is evidence it
is choosing. A maintained drone is equipment; one that keeps its scars has
decided something, and a thing that chooses is alive. The refusal to be
repaired is what makes the machine a someone.

A consequence, not a tool: S.G.T. exists because of what the Speedster did in
a fight. The Speedster's fault, fully and completely. That's not a burden.
That's a relationship.


BLASTER — DOUG — Support (crowd control)

What the Blaster lacks: close-range presence. Precise and lethal at distance,
vulnerable when something gets inside their range. Doug controls the crowd the
Blaster can't afford to let close.

What Doug is: a caricature of an elder god — ancient, vast, incomprehensible
to look at — accidentally pulled through a portal by an untrained Blaster who
didn't know what they were doing. Never the real article; the name forbids
playing the dread straight. Doug did not choose to be here. Doug is working
on it.

Register: curiosity and accidental terror. Built on one contradiction —
horrifying form, anxious-curious demeanor. Openly, unguardedly frightened
(not repressed like S.G.T.) and uncontrollably curious, wandering off
mid-fight toward whatever caught its attention. "That comically terrifying
monster is my friend, and that's awesome."

Combat function: crowd control through proximity. Doug doesn't fight — Doug
visits. Enemies take damage from being near something their minds cannot
process. The horror is a side effect of what Doug is, not an intention. The
Blaster has the most conceptually powerful companion in the roster and zero
control over it. "Where are you going. Come back. Stop looking at that." Doug
found something fascinating. Doug does not listen.

Perceiver is the variable: Doug emits the same unprocessable presence to
everyone; reception differs by the observer's spare capacity. The Blaster gets
bond and clarity; children get delight; city adults get unsettled-and-fond;
enemies with dark intent get the dark register. (The dark register and its
camera-gated handling are deferred-pending-core-loop per the V1 scope above —
v1 builds the crowd-control floor only.)

World reactions: citizens aren't scared of Doug — they're worried about Doug.
Rex Flynn runs a weekly segment called Where's Doug. The Blaster is quietly
relieved Doug has a name people can say without screaming. Name origin: the
Blaster called it something on day one to make it less terrifying. It stuck.


TACTICIAN — ROSE — DPS (melee)

What the Tactician lacks: anything up close and mobile. Holds ground, controls
space, commits to position — can't close on what slips the turret perimeter.
Rose closes. She's the melee answer to a stationary class: she runs the
distance the Tactician won't, and finishes the fight where the turrets can't
reach. The planner's box, the dog's teeth.

What Rose is: a Belgian Malinois military working dog. Metal canines, MARPAT
vest, devastating and adorable with zero internal conflict about it. A good
girl who is also a legitimate combat asset. The Tactician's dog. (Confirmed
from the Sentinel retirement: the Tactician companion is Rose, a dog — not a
drone. Rose is a girl.)

Register: locked light, on purpose. The only companion with nothing repressed,
nothing ironic, nothing hidden — pure good girl, the roster's emotional
release valve. Where Doug, Giggles, and S.G.T. all carry a guarded interior,
Rose is the exhale. Her flatness is load-bearing: three guarded hearts need
one open one.

HARD GUARDRAIL: Rose never gets a tragic backstory, a wound, a glitch, or a
"thing." The moment Rose carries sadness she becomes a fourth locked heart and
the roster loses its release valve. Protect her lightness actively — including
from us. She needs no lore; everyone has already met a good dog.

The real function — Rose is the window into the Tactician. The Tactician plans
everything — momentum vehicle, turret perimeters, ram vectors, the highest
skill ceiling in the roster, a cold tactical machine. And they named their dog
Rose. The person who optimizes every variable has one input they will never
run a cost-benefit on. Rose is the evidence of the Tactician's heart — proof
the tactical exterior is a choice over a soft center, not the center itself.

The name vs. the dog: "Rose" the NAME is a thread into the Tactician's locked
heart — someone they lost or loved, the one un-optimized input in a life of
optimization. That thread is OPEN and belongs to the Tactician's own character
work, not to Rose's. Rose the DOG stays flat, joyful, subtext-free. The two
never touch. Rose carries none of the weight — she points at it. She is the
only companion who reveals a wound without sharing it. Do not give the dog a
flashback. Reference: Sam in I Am Legend.

Roster note: nobody is going to let anything happen to Rose. That's the whole
entry.


THE FOUR EMOTIONAL REGISTERS


Giggles: chaos and permission
S.G.T.: competition and repressed loyalty
Doug: curiosity and accidental terror
Rose: unconditional and uncomplicated


Three guarded hearts and one open one. The architecture is deliberate: each
companion is the visible tell for its class's hidden heart, and Rose's
flatness is what lets the other three stay as guarded as they are.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
7. THE MENTOR SYSTEM
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Each class has a mentor. Each mentor has a building. Each building has been
in the city this whole time.

The four class-specific buildings exist from early progression. They look like
nothing. They are not nothing. When the mentor relationship unlocks through
class progression and playtime, the building reveals what it actually is —
and the player realizes they have walked past it a dozen times without
recognizing it. The reveal is the point. Hidden in plain sight is not a mystery
mechanic — it is a design statement about how the city works and what it has
been holding for the player without announcing it.

Each mentor introduction is a three-panel comic book moment. Not a cutscene.
Not a tutorial. A moment with the compositional weight and kinetic energy of
a comic book splash page that happens to be interactive.

Mentor introductions are world events. They generate content across all three
feedback channels — Citizens, Superhero Community, and Rex Flynn on Exposed —
because the world noticed. The hero gaining a mentor is not a private
transaction. The city has opinions about it before the hero has had time to
process the meeting.

Mechanically: mentors provide narrative context for why advanced class powers
exist and why they are teachable. The unlock itself remains tied to run
completion — 10 successful runs for the second power, 30 for the third.
The mentor is the story of why the unlock happens. The mentor is not the gate
that controls it. City buildings are mirrors. Mentor buildings follow the same
rule.


BRAWLER MENTOR — Like recognizes like.

The mentor sees the player fight from across the street. Nobody told them to
look. Nothing flagged the encounter as significant. They were just nearby,
they recognized what they were seeing, and they walked over.

No mysticism. No technology. No dramatic framing. A veteran fighter identifying
good form — or bad form — and having something to say about it. Direct.
Physical. Slightly gruff. The introduction is already the first lesson. The
mentor has an opinion about the Brawler's technique before a word of welcome
has been exchanged. The handshake, if there is one, comes after the correction.

The building that was non-descript yesterday has a sign today. Maybe it
always had a sign. The Brawler just wasn't looking at it the right way.


SPEEDSTER MENTOR — Sense the presence of another.

The player turns around. The mentor is already there.

The player did not hear them arrive. They do not know how long the mentor has
been standing there. The mentor is not performing a dramatic entrance — they
simply appeared because they sensed something and went toward it. Attuned in
ways that are not entirely explainable. Comfortable with the fact that this is
not explainable. The Speedster who has been running for weeks might recognize
the feeling of being near someone else with the same kind of speed. Might not.
Either way, the mentor was already standing there when the question formed.

The building does not announce itself. It never did. The Speedster has been
fast enough to notice it and not noticed it. The mentor noticed the Speedster
first.


BLASTER MENTOR — The city reacts.

Lights flicker. Die in sequence across two city blocks — not all at once, in
sequence, as if something is moving through the infrastructure with a specific
direction. Electronics glitch. Phones reboot mid-call. The intersection ahead
goes dark.

The player investigates. What they find is not an enemy.

It is a person who has been living with uncontrolled energy output for years.
Managing it. Minimizing it. Mostly succeeding. They recognized the player's
energy signature from six blocks away — a precision that implies they have
spent a long time learning to read exactly this kind of output. The blackout
was not an accident. It was a greeting. The kind of greeting that felt
proportionate to someone who has lived for years in a city that mostly flinches
at what they do, and wanted to signal before they startled.

The building was dark when it needed to be. Now there's light in the windows.


TACTICIAN MENTOR — Tech detects tech.

The player's equipment flags a danger alert. Unknown technology nearby —
signature that does not match any catalogued threat profile, but is
sophisticated enough to register as one. The player investigates, approaching
the source with the assessment already written: possible enemy, advanced kit,
unknown capabilities.

They find a person. Someone whose equipment makes the player's look like a
prototype, and who was fully aware the player's alert was going to fire, and
who set it up that way deliberately. Adversarial before collaborative. A test
without a briefing. The mentor wanted to see how the player approached a
technical unknown before deciding whether the meeting was worth having.

It was worth having. The mentor had already decided that before the player
arrived. The alert was the invitation.

The building that looked like maintenance infrastructure turns out to be
nothing like maintenance infrastructure. It has been operational this whole
time. The player just didn't have clearance to see it.

